            <thetext>A typical scenario for a blocker element is adding some layer element to the web page and to not let the user click at any other element while this layer element is visible.
Another scenario is e.g. a kind of auto-completion where an INPUT element is extended by a DIV element which holds suggestions. For this kind of auto completion one need a blocker element to prevent a &quot;click through&quot;.

In order to support such scenarios a low-level blocker class should be introduced which handles all necessary actions for the application developer.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
